64 5.63604C20.0518 7.32387 21 9.61305 21 12V18" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path><path d="M21 19C21 19.5304 20.7893 20.0391 20.4142 20.4142C20.0391 20.7893 19.5304 21 19 21H18C17.4696 21 16.9609 20.7893 16.5858 20.4142C16.2107 20.0391 16 19.5304 16 19V16C16 15.4696 16.2107 14.9609 16.5858 14.5858C16.9609 14.2107 17.4696 14 18 14H21V19ZM3 19C3 19.5304 3.21071 20.0391 3.58579 20.4142C3.96086 20.7893 4.46957 21 5 21H6C6.53043 21 7.03914 20.7893 7.41421 20.4142C7.78929 20.0391 8 19.5304 8 19V16C8 15.4696 7.78929 14.9609 7.41421 14.5858C7.03914 14.2107 6.53043 14 6 14H3V19Z" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path></svg></div><div class="embedded-post-title"> PODCAST：Hexapodia LIX：德隆 Smackdown 观看：中国版</div></div><div class="embedded-post-body">Noah Smith &amp; Brad DeLong Record the Podcast We, at Least, Would Like to Listen to!; Aspirationally Bi-Weekly (Meaning Every Other Week); Aspirationally an hour… </div><div class="embedded-post-cta-wrapper"><div class="embedded-post-cta-icon"><svg width="32" height="32" viewBox="0 0 24 24" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><path classname="inner-triangle" d="M10 8L16 12L10 16V8Z" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"></path></svg></div><span class="embedded-post-cta">现在听</span></div><div class="embedded-post-meta">17 天前 · 11 个赞 · 5 条评论 · 布拉德·德隆和诺亚·史密斯</div></div><p>Anyway, on to this week&#39;s list of interesting things!有几周我会用综述来涵盖一些我在较长的帖子中没有提到的事情。但本周我将利用这次综述作为机会，谈谈我的一些标准爱好——与中国和俄罗斯的竞争、通货膨胀、产业政策和移民。</p><h4> 1. 为什么世界上大部分国家都会追随美国的关税</h4><p>经济学中有一个古老的理论，叫做<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stackelberg_competition">斯塔克尔伯格竞争</a>博弈。不是所有公司都试图同时设定价格，而是由一家重要的公司为其他公司设定价格。这个游戏基本上已经成为<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stackelberg_competition#Applications">任何有一个或多个先行者和一个或多个追随者的情况</a>的心理替身。一些人<a href="https://dash.harvard.edu/bitstream/handle/1/3450062/helpman_tradewars.pdf?sequence=4">使用斯塔克尔伯格型模型</a>来分析国际<a href="https://pubs.aip.org/aip/acp/article-abstract/1479/1/1155/875670/International-Stackelberg-model-with-tariffs?redirectedFrom=PDF">贸易政策</a>，还有一些人甚至将这一想法应用于中美<a href="https://dl.acm.org/doi/10.1145/3472349.3472363">竞争</a>。</p><p>我怀疑在某个时候，有人会写一篇关于目前世界各地正在形成的<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-big-tariffs-are-here">贸易战</a>的斯塔克尔伯格式的论文。总体而言，中国是这场游戏的“领导者”，因为正是中国大量的制成品出口促使其他国家考虑采取保护主义措施。但在关税方面，美国似乎作为先行者发挥了重要作用： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg" width="922" height="314" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:314,&quot;width&quot;:922,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:60275,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa6fc59b4-3e78-4b1a-b190-1a98feb05f4b_922x314.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>迪斯是拜登最重要的经济顾问之一，因此当政府决定推出引人注目的巨额关税时，其他国家也会效仿的想法很可能在政府的思维中发挥了作用。</p><p>那么迪斯是对的吗？世界正在追随美国吗？<em>从政治上来说</em>，我想说答案是“不”。早在拜登宣布之前，欧盟就<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-03-06/eu-moves-toward-hitting-china-with-tariffs-on-electric-vehicles?sref=R8NfLgwS">开始对中国电动汽车征收关税</a>。巴西已经<a href="https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/brazil-imports-chinese-electric-vehicles-surge-ahead-new-tariff-2024-04-05/">提高了</a>对中国汽车和<a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-04-23/brazil-joins-protectionist-wave-in-face-of-cheap-steel-imports?sref=R8NfLgwS">其他产品的</a>关税。 <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-02-15/thailand-weighs-tax-on-cheap-chinese-goods-hurting-local-firms?sref=R8NfLgwS">泰国也有</a>。这些国家都不需要美国的“许可”来保护其国内企业。</p><p>但从<em>经济角度</em>来看，我认为世界将被迫追随美国的领导。尽管中国出口激增的<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-china-producing-so-many-export">可能原因有多种</a>，但有一点似乎确实是事实：至少目前来看，中国的生产是由<em>内部</em>激励决定的，而不是由海外发生的任何事情决定的。这意味着，如果关税阻止中国电动汽车和其他商品进入美国，中国企业不会简单地关闭其生产线。他们将继续生产，并尝试将产品销往其他地方——印度、欧盟、东南亚、拉丁美洲等。</p><p>换句话说，美国的关税将使第二次中国冲击对其他人来说更加严重。这将增加其他所有人效仿美国关税来做出回应的压力。随着越来越多的国家提高关税，大量的中国商品将被压缩到越来越小的目的地国家。最终，即使是最不情愿的保护主义者也将面临如此巨大的低价进口浪潮，以至于他们的当地企业将向政府咆哮，要求政府做出回应。</p><p> <a href="https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/us-trade-curbs-china-may-lead-dumping-chinese-goods-india-ydwkf/">印度</a>和欧盟<a href="https://www.cnn.com/2024/05/15/business/us-tariffs-ev-europe-china-trade/index.html">已经</a>对此表示强烈担忧。他们可能不像美国那样倾向于采取迅速、剧烈的保护主义措施。但现在他们国内制造业面临的压力比美国更大，所以可能会一个接一个地传到世界各地。美国可能在关税问题上发挥了政治领导作用，也可能没有，但这可能是多米诺骨牌连锁中的第一张。</p><h4> 2.中国和俄罗斯想要统治你的信息空间</h4><p>说到国际竞争，我们来谈谈信息战。</p><p> 《世界其他地区》最近发表了<a href="https://restofworld.org/2024/tiktok-chinese-us-ban/">一篇关于 TikTok 与中国关系的精彩文章</a>。一些摘录：</p><blockquote><p>十几名现任和前任美国 TikTok 员工接受了<em>《世界其他地区》</em>采访，其中大多数人因担心公司报复而要求匿名，他们表示 TikTok 与字节跳动的关系比该公司所展示的更进一步。他们说字节跳动的高管，而不是[首席执行官受子]周，管理着由数千名美国 TikTok 员工组成的关键部门……</p><p>在内部，员工和管理人员将公司称为“字节跳动”和“TikTok”，因为大多数技术团队与中国抖音员工密切合作。 TikTok 的一位高级工程师告诉<em>《世界其他地区》，</em>他估计技术团队（包括软件工程师、产品经理和用户体验设计师）有 40% 至 60% 的成员在中国。</p></blockquote><p>毫无疑问，目前 TikTok 正在<a href="https://x.com/cremieuxrecueil/status/1783954180970815987">审查其不喜欢的主题的美国人视频</a>，并向中国政府提供大量有关美国人（以及加拿大人和其他所有人）的个人数据。加拿大情报机构最近<a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/5/17/24159310/canadian-security-intelligence-service-tiktok-china-user-data">警告公民</a>出于隐私考虑不要使用 TikTok。</p><p>与此同时，TikTok 远非中国信息战的唯一载体。该国在<a href="https://www.wired.com/story/china-bad-at-disinformation/">美国社交媒体上充斥着</a>机器人和人工操作的账户，试图传播虚假信息和分裂性信息：</p><blockquote><p>在过去的 24 个月里，该活动已经从主要推动亲中国的内容转向更<a href="https://www.dni.gov/files/ODNI/documents/assessments/ATA-2024-Unclassified-Report.pdf">积极地针对美国政治</a>……作为中国政府<a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-is-investing-billions-in-global-disinformation-campaign-u-s-says-88740b85#:~:text=WASHINGTON%E2%80%94The%20Chinese%20government%20is,a%20new%20State%20Department%20assessment.">数十亿美元影响力活动</a>的一部分，该活动使用了数十个互联网平台上的数百万个帐户从 X 和 YouTube 到 Gab 等更多边缘平台，该活动一直试图在这些平台上推广亲中国的内容。它也是最早采用<a href="https://cyberscoop.com/graphika-spamouflage-dragon-china/">人工智能生成个人资料图片</a>等尖端技术的公司之一……在过去的五年里，一直跟踪该活动的研究人员观察到它试图改变策略，使用视频、自动配音和最近，采用人工智能来创建个人资料图像和内容，旨在激怒现有部门。</p></blockquote><p>到目前为止，他们的努力是笨拙、分散且无效的。但他们最终可能会知道什么有效，什么无效。</p><p>中国还可以获得更传统的代理人。网络传染研究所有一份关于与中共有联系的美国商人内维尔·罗伊·辛厄姆（Neville Roy Singham）经营的影响者网络的<a href="https://networkcontagion.us/wp-content/uploads/SID4P-Report_May-2024.pdf">精彩报告</a>。该网络负责组织一些最极端的巴勒斯坦抗议活动。</p><p>与此同时，中国可能正在加强与俄罗斯在信息战领域的合作。最近在北京举行的一次峰会上，普京和习近平<a href="https://x.com/ArturRehi/status/1791518907133526067">同意让两国的新闻机构更加密切地协调</a>。俄罗斯缺乏中国的原材料，但它参与这场游戏的时间要长得多，并且更了解美国社会的分裂。</p><p>这场信息战对美国对待媒体和言论自由的方式提出了严峻的挑战。几十年来，美国实际上采用了诺齐克式的自由主义思想，即美国政府是一个全能的主权国家，必须在信息空间中完全克制自己；同时，这种观点认为，外国政府对于美国个人而言是微小的原子化行为体，因此必须不受任何干涉。</p><p>这种方法在美国超级大国时代可能是有意义的，甚至苏联的宣传工作也可能不会给该系统带来太大压力。但随着社交媒体的出现，以及比我们拥有更多经济资源的外国政府对美国进行大规模中央指导的宣传活动，诺齐克式的媒体监管自由主义观点看起来越来越站不住脚，而且会弄巧成拙。这是自由主义的大考验。</p><h4> 3. 这是通货膨胀，笨蛋！</h4><p>尽管经济强劲且<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-positive-case-for-joe-biden">总统任期总体成功</a>，乔·拜登的民调数字<a href="https://www.axios.com/2024/05/14/biden-polls-denial-trump-2024-election">仍然表现不佳</a>。而一次又一次的民意调查揭示了拜登表现不佳的原因：通货膨胀。这是<a href="https://www.ft.com/content/46c6cc07-ec71-4d8b-a630-9c39f5856b7c">英国《金融时报</a>》：</p><blockquote><p>英国《金融时报》的一项新民意调查显示，乔·拜登的连任前景受到对通胀持续担忧的困扰，80%的选民表示，高物价是他们面临的最大财务挑战之一。尽管去年稳步下降，但几个月来通胀再次上升。它们扭转了美国总统近期在处理美国经济问题上在选民中取得的进展。</p></blockquote><p> <a href="https://abcnews.go.com/Business/trump-trusted-biden-inflation-top-issue-voters-poll/story?id=110343680">这是ABC</a> ：</p><blockquote><p>根据本月美国广播公司新闻/益普索的一项新民意调查，美国成年人在<a href="https://abcnews.go.com/Business/inflation-expected-cooled-slightly-april/story?id=110166979">通货膨胀</a>问题上对前总统唐纳德·特朗普的信任度超过了对总统乔·拜登的信任度，该民意调查发现，物价上涨仍然是选民最关心的问题……总而言之， 85% 的民意调查参与者表示，通货膨胀是一个重要问题，使其成为受访成年人中第二重要的问题。最优先考虑的 <a href="https://abcnews.go.com/Business/us-economy-cooling-off-experts-worry/story?id=109692759">经济</a>问题也与个人对物价上涨的看法有关……在经济和通胀等问题上，接受美国广播公司新闻/益普索调查的成年人表示，他们对特朗普的信任度比拜登高出 14 个百分点。</p></blockquote><p>通货膨胀率仍较 2021-22 年低很多。但到了今年头几个月，它又重新加速了一点，这可能让人感到相当害怕。这是一张好照片： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg" width="480" height="361" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:361,&quot;width&quot;:480,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:65228,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F2f4dd052-c014-40e4-90b1-519b7ad944e6_480x361.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源：<a href="https://x.com/jasonfurman/status/1790876088463142995">贾森·弗曼</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>经历 2021-22 年之后，人们仍然感到恐慌，这是可以理解的。但最近的飙升不仅仅是暂时的上涨——基本通胀率<a href="https://x.com/jasonfurman/status/1790876083383877796">约为 3.5%</a> ，这远远高于新冠疫情之前的水平。</p><p>没有人真正知道是什么导致了通货膨胀，但目前我们知道，这不是石油（已经回落），不是大流行性供应链中断（早已不复存在），也不是被压抑的——增加大流行病带来的积蓄（已经全部花完）。这也不是胡塞武装对红海航运的袭击，因为美国的通胀<a href="https://x.com/jasonfurman/status/1790726671575785907">完全集中在租金等服务价格上</a>，而不是实物商品价格上。最有可能的罪魁祸首是<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-the-us-doing-so-much-deficit">美国的高赤字支出</a>——一些进步人士称之为“大财政”。</p><p>这让拜登陷入了困境。在大选前削减赤字来降低通胀为时已晚——即使拜登明<em>天</em>通过紧缩预算，也只会在短期内损害经济，而且要到 11 月之后很久才能降低通胀。因此，总统为美国人提供救济的唯一方法就是向他们扔钱： </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg" width="676" height="265.80941949616647" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/e723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:359,&quot;width&quot;:913,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:676,&quot;bytes&quot;:64037,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fe723d601-182e-4bee-8252-c9636f1b5c00_913x359.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p>从长远来看，这只会让问题变得更糟。在不增加供应的情况下补贴住房会提高租金。这是拜登在不增加供应的情况下补贴价格过高的服务业的不幸模式的一部分，但在这种情况下，它甚至没有创造任何就业机会——它只是流向了房东。</p><p>但从短期来看，拜登在大选前可能无能为力，无法帮助选民感觉自己的生活便宜了一些。那真不幸。</p><h4> 4. 马特·伊格莱西亚斯（Matt Yglesias）产业政策的两条原则</h4><p>马特·伊格莱西亚斯（Matt Yglesias）前几天发表了一篇关于产业政策的精彩（付费）帖子： </p><div class="embedded-post-wrap" data-attrs="{&quot;id&quot;:143947056,&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.slowboring.com/p/friday-grab-bag-taking-industrial&quot;,&quot;publication_id&quot;:159185,&quot;publication_name&quot;:&quot;Slow Boring &quot;,&quot;publication_logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fceeb681e-a14d-4bbb-a8fe-951c29603e3f_256x256.png&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;Friday Grab Bag: Taking industrial policy seriously &quot;,&quot;truncated_body_text&quot;:&quot;We are back from a refreshing trip to Jamaica, which also offered an opportunity to revisit Rasheed Griffith&#8217;s February piece &#8220;Jamaica is Not Doing Okay&#8221; taking a skeptical look at recent economic trends on the island. It&#8217;s a great article and in general I wish Americans paid more attention to economic development questions in the Western Hemisphere because these things actually have large impacts on events in the United States in a way that sexier issues in the Middle East don&#8217;t.&quot;,&quot;date&quot;:&quot;2024-04-26T10:01:43.328Z&quot;,&quot;like_count&quot;:143,&quot;comment_count&quot;:264,&quot;bylines&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:580004,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Matthew Yglesias&quot;,&quot;handle&quot;:&quot;matthewyglesias&quot;,&quot;previous_name&quot;:null,&quot;photo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/20964455-401a-494d-a8ef-9835b34e9809_3024x3024.png&quot;,&quot;bio&quot;:&quot;Blogger, journalist, podcaster, trying to get back to my roots. &quot;,&quot;profile_set_up_at&quot;:&quot;2021-04-21T11:11:05.347Z&quot;,&quot;publicationUsers&quot;:[{&quot;id&quot;:18017,&quot;user_id&quot;:580004,&quot;publication_id&quot;:159185,&quot;role&quot;:&quot;admin&quot;,&quot;public&quot;:true,&quot;is_primary&quot;:false,&quot;publication&quot;:{&quot;id&quot;:159185,&quot;name&quot;:&quot;Slow Boring &quot;,&quot;subdomain&quot;:&quot;matthewyglesias&quot;,&quot;custom_domain&quot;:&quot;www.slowboring.com&quot;,&quot;custom_domain_optional&quot;:false,&quot;hero_text&quot;:&quot;Start your day with pragmatic takes on politics and public policy.&quot;,&quot;logo_url&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/ceeb681e-a14d-4bbb-a8fe-951c29603e3f_256x256.png&quot;,&quot;author_id&quot;:580004,&quot;theme_var_background_pop&quot;:&quot;#121BFA&quot;,&quot;created_at&quot;:&quot;2020-11-05T16:20:32.177Z&quot;,&quot;rss_website_url&quot;:null,&quot;email_from_name&quot;:&quot;Matthew Yglesias&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;Matthew Yglesias&quot;,&quot;founding_plan_name&quot;:&quot;Charismatic Authority&quot;,&quot;community_enabled&quot;:true,&quot;invite_only&quot;:false,&quot;payments_state&quot;:&quot;enabled&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:null,&quot;explicit&quot;:false}}],&quot;twitter_screen_name&quot;:&quot;mattyglesias&quot;,&quot;is_guest&quot;:false,&quot;bestseller_tier&quot;:10000}],&quot;utm_campaign&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;newsletter&quot;,&quot;language&quot;:&quot;en&quot;}" data-component-name="EmbeddedPostToDOM"><a class="embedded-post" native="true" href="https://www.slowboring.com/p/friday-grab-bag-taking-industrial?utm_source=substack&amp;utm_campaign=post_embed&amp;utm_medium=web"><div class="embedded-post-header"><img class="embedded-post-publication-logo" src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_56,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fceeb681e-a14d-4bbb-a8fe-951c29603e3f_256x256.png" loading="lazy"> <span class="embedded-post-publication-name">Slow Boring</span></div><div class="embedded-post-title-wrapper"><div class="embedded-post-title">周五抢包：认真对待产业政策</div></div><div class="embedded-post-body">我们结束了令人耳目一新的牙买加之旅，这次旅行也提供了重温拉希德·格里菲斯 (Rasheed Griffith) 二月文章“牙买加做得不好”的机会，对岛上最近的经济趋势持怀疑态度。这是一篇很棒的文章，总的来说，我希望美国人更多地关注西半球的经济发展问题，因为这些事情实际上对美国发生的事件有很大的影响，而中东更性感的问题却不会……</div><div class="embedded-post-cta-wrapper"><span class="embedded-post-cta">阅读更多</span></div><div class="embedded-post-meta">一个月前 · 143 个赞 · 264 条评论 · 马修·伊格莱西亚斯</div></div><p>这是一篇“抓包”帖子（很像这个），所以我想提取一些亮点以确保它们不会被忽视。我特别认为他对产业政策有两个很好的见解，应该成为美国政治家的指导原则。</p><p>首先，产业政策不仅仅是保护主义。事实上，当我们<em>最大限度地</em>扩大与盟友和朋友的贸易时，产业政策就会变得更好；</p><blockquote><p>任何与中国加强战略竞争的政策都需要以与日本、韩国、澳大利亚和其他亚洲盟友建立更密切的关系为前提，而不是把它们视为敌人。</p></blockquote><p>这非常重要，不仅是因为地缘战略问题，还因为经济问题。中国成为如此庞大的制造业巨兽的原因之一是他们拥有巨大的统一国内市场。美国的面积只有中国的 1/4，无法匹敌其内部市场。日本或其他较小的国家也不能。印度也不能，它的人口比中国多，但穷得多。</p><p>非中国国家要想获得与中国竞争的市场规模，唯一的方法就是<strong>整合它们的市场</strong>。我们需要让美国、欧洲、日本、韩国和印度降低彼此之间的贸易和投资壁垒，尽管它们对中国的出口设置了壁垒。只有这个庞大的综合市场才能为制造企业带来可与中国相媲美的规模经济。</p><p>马特的另一个优点是产业政策的目标应该是<em>生产</em>而不是<em>制造业就业</em>：</p><blockquote><p>如果我们想要国内芯片生产，那就值得花钱，是的，但也值得为该行业提供监管支持。这意味着为该行业所需的工人移民提供便利，让他们摆脱环境监管，最重要的是，促进生产力和效率的最大化，而不是优先考虑“创造就业机会”和“好就业机会”。</p></blockquote><p>这是绝对正确的。产业政策将创造大量就业机会，但大部分不是在装配线上。为了让美国能够与中国竞争，这些都必须实现<em>自动化</em>，中国正在以<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-factories-accelerate-robotics-push-as-workforce-shrinks-11663493405">极快的速度</a>实现自己的装配线自动化。相反，产业政策将通过<a href="https://eml.berkeley.edu/~moretti/multipliers.pdf">当地乘数的魔力</a>创造良好的就业机会——自动化制造带来的资金将在当地地区和当地服务业中重新分配。</p><p>因此，良好的产业政策应侧重于自动化制造，而不是在 20 世纪 40 年代风格的低效装配线上提供制造工作。</p><h4> 5.关于移民的一个非常好的主意</h4><p>我<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/america-please-be-reasonable-on-immigration">非常亲密移民</a>，我认为<a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-skilled-immigration-usually-benefits">高技能的移民</a>是最重要的。 But I recognize that amid all the hyperpartisan shouting and scare-mongering, there are important and real challenges to be overcome when bringing large numbers of skilled workers into our country.</p><p> The biggest is the <em>housing problem</em> — when a bunch of high-earning workers flood into already expensive coastal cities like San Francisco and LA, it exacerbates the NIMBY-driven housing crunch in those areas. Yes, we should build more housing and overcome the NIMBYs, but that&#39;s much easier said than done — skilled immigration to superstar coastal metros makes YIMBY politics into a bit of a treadmill. Meanwhile, Rust Belt areas that could benefit the most from skilled immigration often languish, because immigrants don&#39;t move there.</p><p> One way to solve this is to help direct immigrants to areas other than San Francisco and Los Angeles. Canada does this by <a href="https://www.canadim.com/immigrate/provincial-nominee-program/">allowing provinces to sponsor immigrants</a> like employers do. The US should do something along these lines. And the Economic Innovation Group, one of my favorite policy think tanks, has a proposal for how we could send skilled immigrants to Rust Belt areas where they&#39;re needed most.他们称其为<a href="https://eig.org/heartland-visas-a-policy-primer/">心脏地带签证</a>：</p><blockquote><p> The Heartland Visa is an innovative proposal that gives communities the choice to opt-in to a new immigration pathway for highly skilled workers, entrepreneurs, and innovators. Prioritizing higher-earning applicants and those with local ties, the Heartland Visa would serve as a key component of economic revitalization in participating places.</p><p> In exchange for living in a Heartland Visa community, workers with sufficient earnings will gain permanent residency, cutting through burdensome red tape and bureaucracy embedded in the status quo immigration system. Building on our 2019 concept paper, this report details how we can make Heartland Visas a reality on the ground.</p><p> <strong>Key Features of a Heartland Visa</strong></p><ul><li><p> <strong>Dual opt-in</strong> : Counties experiencing economic decline or stagnation can decide to opt in or out of the program, while applicants select their own destinations.</p></li><li><p> <strong>Prioritize applicants with high-wage job offers</strong> : Applicants are allocated quarterly to those with the highest job offers or earnings histories, adjusted for age and local ties.</p></li><li><p> <strong>Pathway to permanent residency</strong> : Heartland Visa holders, in exchange for living in a participating community for six years, should have an expedited path to a green card.</p></li><li><p> <strong>Scale</strong> : Heartland Visas should be large enough to fundamentally change the economic trajectory of participating communities for the better.</p></li></ul></blockquote><p> And here&#39;s a picture of the areas that would be eligible for Heartland Visas: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg" width="1140" height="720" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:720,&quot;width&quot;:1140,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:221464,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa1edd8e0-4daa-4bd7-9fe0-15b4d33ab8b7_1140x720.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://eig.org/heartland-visas-a-policy-primer/">EIG</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> This is a great idea, and we should adopt it as soon as we can. Declining regions in the US can greatly benefit from having talented workers. Their high salaries mean that they will be a huge fiscal boon to struggling cities and states. And these workers&#39; presence will lure corporate investment, boosting local tax revenues and causing positive multiplier effects throughout local economies.</p><h4> 6. An easy way to lose your money</h4><p> Although I talk about financial issues a fair amount on this blog, I strenuously avoid giving specific financial advice about what assets you should buy. But not everyone is so scrupulous. Tons of financial gurus out there are extremely eager to tell you which stocks you should pick, which crypto coins you should grab, how to time the market, and so on. And most of them end up losing money for their faithful followers.</p><p> That&#39;s the conclusion of <a href="https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=4428232">a new paper by Kakhbod et al.</a> (hat tip to <a href="https://x.com/kylascan/status/1791810497249165763">Kyla Scanlon</a> for the find). The paper, entitled “Finfluencers”, scans a bunch of tweets from StockTwits, and finds that the advice these influencers offer to the public tends to be quite bad:</p><blockquote><p> This paper assesses the quality of investment advice provided by different finfluencers. Using tweet-level data from StockTwits on over 29,000 finfluencers, we classify each finfluencer into three major groups: Skilled, unskilled, and antiskilled, defined as those with negative skill. We find that 28% of finfluencers provide valuable investment advice that leads to monthly abnormal returns of 2.6% on average, while 16% of them are unskilled. The majority of finfluencers, 56%, are antiskilled and following their investment advice yields monthly abnormal returns of -2.3%. Surprisingly, unskilled and antiskilled finfluencers have more followers, more activity, and more influence on retail trading than skilled finfluencers.</p></blockquote><p> In other words, the more attention a “finfluencer” gets, the worse advice they tend to give. There are a minority of smart advice-givers out there, but regular folks are very bad at picking which ones they are.</p><p> If you think about it, this just flows directly from the Efficient Markets Hypothesis — which, though not formally true, is a great heuristic guide for investors to think about why it&#39;s hard to beat the market. The key question to ask yourself is: <em>If you&#39;re not smart enough to pick your own stocks, what makes you smart enough to pick a financial guru to pick your stocks for you?</em> And if gurus have to allocate their scarce personal resources of time, thought, and attention to either A) picking good stocks, or B) shilling for attention, it stands to reason that the ones who specialize in the latter will be less good at the以前的。</p><p> Anyway, no matter what you invest in, you should always think twice before deciding you can beat the market. That&#39;s true whether you pick your own assets or get your ideas from some influencer on Twitter. </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-585?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/at-least-five-interesting-things-585?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p>; 
Why is China producing so many export goods, anyway?Six theories. https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-china-producing-so-many-export https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-china-producing-so-many-exportNoah Smith Fri, 17 May 2024 23:38:46 GMT <div class="captioned-image-container"><figure> <a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg" width="710" height="473.57507660878446" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:653,&quot;width&quot;:979,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:710,&quot;bytes&quot;:62914,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:true,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F200bdd18-a6c4-4583-852d-1a7fc2301ec8_979x653.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" fetchpriority="high"></picture></div></a> <polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line><figcaption class="image-caption"> Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@diegitane?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=unsplash">Diego Fernandez</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com/photos/black-and-red-ship-on-body-of-water-at-daytime-6Vg8N8u61aI?utm_content=creditCopyText&amp;utm_medium=referral&amp;utm_source=unsplash">Unsplash</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The big economic news this week was Biden&#39;s <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2024/05/14/fact-sheet-president-biden-takes-action-to-protect-american-workers-and-businesses-from-chinas-unfair-trade-practices/">very large tariffs</a> on a number of Chinese-made goods. Those tariffs appear to have acted as a catalyst for a bunch of other countries — India, Brazil, Vietnam, Thailand, Mexico, the EU, etc. — to <a href="https://x.com/BrianCDeese/status/1790815108915933515">consider their own tariffs</a> on China. In other words, much of the world now sees the <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-decade-of-the-second-china-shock">Second China Shock</a> as a danger to their own manufacturing industries, and is acting accordingly.</p><p> This is a huge, momentous shift. A year and a half ago, when <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/the-end-of-the-system-of-the-world">I declared</a> that the global economic system that had defined the previous 2-3 decades was now breaking down, some people naturally thought I had overstated my case. Now even critics of the shift are forced to admit that <a href="https://www.economist.com/briefing/2024/05/09/the-worlds-economic-order-is-breaking-down">a new era is upon us</a> .</p><p> What the era of decoupling, competition, and fragmentation means for the world, and how to manage it effectively, will be the subject of a huge amount of discussion and analysis (and Noahpinion blog posts) in the years to come. But for right now, an interesting question that I think deserves more thought is: <em>Why is China exporting so much stuff?</em> Most of the new trade barriers and industrial policies that we see popping up all over the world are either directly or indirectly China-related. The new tariffs are explicitly in response to China&#39;s vast and rising trade surplus in manufactured goods: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg" width="680" height="494" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/a94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:494,&quot;width&quot;:680,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:61207,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Fa94ce5ef-bd23-4f18-84a6-6b03da608f60_680x494.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://www.cfr.org/blog/chinas-record-manufacturing-surplus">CFR</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> There are a number of theories floating around out there about why Chinese cars, chips, steel, solar panels, machinery, and other goods are flooding world markets. The theories aren&#39;t generally mutually exclusive — it could be some combination of any or all of these. But I thought it would be useful to gather all the hypotheses in one list.</p><h4> Theory 1: Economic stimulus</h4><p> In the 2000s, Chinese exports soared even as the Chinese economy was also powering ahead with rapid growth. The two went hand in hand. The 2020s are different; China&#39;s exports are booming even as the economy is slowing down. Official statistics say that the country is still growing at a fairly healthy rate of around 5%; independent estimates put the number <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/why-you-shouldnt-trust-chinese-growth-data-c65d1a8c">closer to 1.5%</a> , or <a href="https://www.forbes.com/sites/georgecalhoun/2024/05/04/the-missing-factor-in-explanations-of-chinas-economic-distress-covid-part-1-the-cover-up/?sh=6d892a77c441">even 0%</a> : </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg" width="616" height="412.9802816901408" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:476,&quot;width&quot;:710,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:616,&quot;bytes&quot;:72384,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:false,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F6a2b1a28-35da-4124-ae60-56fc74d34e52_710x476.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div></figure></div><p> The reason for this slowdown is <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-chinas-economy-ran-off-the-rails">a gigantic real estate bust</a> . Real estate and related industries like construction and finance had come to dominate China&#39;s economy, serving as a combination of local government finance, jobs program, and personal savings vehicle. In 2021 the industry started to experience a sharp downturn that is <a href="https://money.usnews.com/investing/news/articles/2024-05-16/china-april-new-home-prices-fall-at-fastest-monthly-pace-in-over-nine-years?src=usn_tw">by no means over</a> .</p><p> The slowdown has destroyed a vast amount of paper household wealth and created a massive buildup of largely hidden bad debts within the banking system. This threatens to cause a rise in joblessness. In the past, China&#39;s government responded to economic shocks by pumping up real estate, but that isn&#39;t working now. So instead, it makes sense to stimulate some other part of the economy. And since Xi Jinping doesn&#39;t seem to believe that consumption and service industries make a country strong, the natural alternative for keeping young Chinese people employed is just to manufacture a whole bunch of stuff.</p><p> Since real estate began to crash, there has been a huge surge in industrial lending in China. Some portion of this has been used as a stealth bailout for distressed sectors, but a lot of it has gone to manufacturing: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg" width="676" height="396.0149253731343" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/f7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:471,&quot;width&quot;:804,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:676,&quot;bytes&quot;:85867,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2Ff7004270-d516-4d57-8fd0-2dd1ffb46d34_804x471.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption">资料来源： <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-05-08/china-s-surging-industrial-loans-are-going-to-the-wrong-places?sref=R8NfLgwS">彭博社</a></figcaption></figure></div><p>Even if this expansion isn&#39;t purely efficient from a supply-side or productivity perspective, it might be worth it from a demand-side perspective — ie, keeping Chinese people working so they don&#39;t get mad at the government.</p><p> So this is the first theory: Industrial expansion as a replacement for the real estate boom.</p><h4> Theory 2: Overcapacity/underconsumption</h4><p> There&#39;s a second, closely related theory that generally goes by the name of “overcapacity”. In a nutshell, the idea is that China&#39;s consumption has slowed down as a result of the real estate bust, but due to government subsidies and other factors, production hasn&#39;t slowed. Thus, Chinese producers who are being paid to make stuff but who can no longer sell it locally are just going to dump <a class="footnote-anchor" data-component-name="FootnoteAnchorToDOM" id="footnote-anchor-1" href="#footnote-1" target="_self">1</a> their product on the world market and hope somebody buys it. Overcapacity is what National Economic Council Director Lael Brainard cited as the main reason for the new tariffs in <a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2024/05/16/remarks-by-national-economic-advisor-lael-brainard-on-responding-to-the-challenges-of-chinas-industrial-overcapacity/">a recent speech</a> :</p><blockquote><p> In part, China&#39;s overcapacity is achieved by firms selling at or <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/21/business/energy-environment/chinese-solar-companys-operating-unit-declares-bankruptcy.html">below cost</a> —enabled by policy decisions that unfairly depress capital, labor, and energy costs…By <a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/chinas-spending-on-green-energy-is-causing-a-global-glut-d80eaea7">undercutting global prices</a> for these goods, Chinese policy-driven overcapacity disrupts the necessary demand signal that would enable market-based investment to be viable.</p></blockquote><p> It&#39;s very difficult to tell whether this is actually happening. The Rhodium Group has a report called “ <a href="https://rhg.com/research/overcapacity-at-the-gate/">Overcapacity at the Gate</a> ”, in which they show that capacity utilization at Chinese factories in subsidized industries has fallen by a lot. That suggests that Chinese companies have built a bunch of factories they&#39;re not using — pretty typical for a country in a recession. But if they&#39;re not using the factories, they can&#39;t be using them to fill export orders either — at least, not yet. So there&#39;s still the question of why they would start using the spare factory capacity instead of just shutting it down.</p><p> One possible answer is “subsidies”. Yoko Kubota and Clarence Leong had a great article in the WSJ about a Chinese auto company that should have gone bust, but was saved by government support:</p><blockquote><p> In 2019, a little-known Chinese carmaker named Zhido went bust after Beijing cut subsidies for the tiny electric cars it made, crushing its sales…Now it is back…Zhido&#39;s rebirth came after state-backed funds and dozens of other investors pumped fresh capital into the company late last year—despite widespread signs that China <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/chinas-overcapacity-is-already-backfiring-86f29e4a?mod=article_inline">has too many carmakers</a> to serve its needs…the government continues to support companies such as Zhido and others, encouraging unprofitable carmakers to keep producing as officials try to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-first-quarter-economic-growth-beats-market-expectations-0d363c90?mod=article_inline">boost economic growth</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-goes-all-in-on-green-industry-to-jolt-ailing-economy-2f836395?mod=article_inline">preserve jobs</a> and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/business/autos/china-offers-support-to-accelerate-ev-makers-global-push-9ae498ff?mod=article_inline">expand China&#39;s role</a> in the global electric-vehicle business.</p></blockquote><p> This isn&#39;t unusual for China. <a href="https://csis-website-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/publication/220523_DiPippo_Red_Ink.pdf?VersionId=LH8ILLKWz4o.bjrwNS7csuX_C04FyEre">A CSIS report in 2022</a> tried to measure China&#39;s total support to manufacturing companies, and the numbers they arrived at were eye-poppingly huge: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg" width="678" height="524.3431498079385" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:604,&quot;width&quot;:781,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:678,&quot;bytes&quot;:82526,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F286eb257-fb82-408b-9a8e-6469658aae20_781x604.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://csis-website-prod.s3.amazonaws.com/s3fs-public/publication/220523_DiPippo_Red_Ink.pdf?VersionId=LH8ILLKWz4o.bjrwNS7csuX_C04FyEre">CSIS</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> So a lot of overcapacity may be driven by these subsidies.</p><p> But there&#39;s actually a second possible reason for overcapacity, which is much more benign from a policy perspective. A country with a very large domestic market may experience <a href="https://theovershoot.co/p/chinese-overcapacity-is-not-the-problem?utm_campaign=post&amp;utm_medium=web">swings in consumption</a> that are so rapid that producers have trouble adjusting their production plans to meet the changes in demand. This can result in swings in imports and exports that look huge from an international perspective, but are actually small compared to the domestic market.</p><p> For example, Chinese domestic vehicle sales have decreased recently, probably as a result of the slowing economy. That slowdown, coupled with roughly flat production, has resulted in a gigantic percentage increase in auto exports, even though those exports are still only one sixth of domestic consumption: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg" width="1422" height="1033" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:1033,&quot;width&quot;:1422,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:187278,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F238e4912-dc56-44b6-8a7d-7b403d3e6738_1422x1033.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://x.com/Brad_Setser/status/1776702149918863586">Brad Setser</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> Similar patterns manifest in <a href="https://x.com/Brad_Setser/status/1776700089634873607">steel</a> and some other industries.</p><p> In fact, China<a href="https://x.com/AgatheDemarais/status/1791045933050069238?t=VneAP4gbwxfYX4RBV5hY5w&amp;s=19">exports far</a> <em><a href="https://x.com/AgatheDemarais/status/1791045933050069238?t=VneAP4gbwxfYX4RBV5hY5w&amp;s=19">fewer</a></em><a href="https://x.com/AgatheDemarais/status/1791045933050069238?t=VneAP4gbwxfYX4RBV5hY5w&amp;s=19">cars</a> as a percent of total production than countries like Japan or Germany. But because China is just so huge, what look like small swings to China are huge, disruptive swings for other countries around the world.</p><p> In the short term, it&#39;s very hard to tell whether overcapacity is being driven by subsidies or by companies simply not being able to adjust quickly to drops in domestic demand. The Rhodium Group <a href="https://rhg.com/research/overcapacity-at-the-gate/">calls these</a> “structural” vs. “temporary” overcapacity. But both versions manifest as a seemingly huge flood of cheap Chinese goods glutting world markets and threatening other countries&#39; manufacturing industries.</p><h4> Theory 3: Comparative advantage</h4><p> China&#39;s leaders, of course, strongly contest the idea that their country is suffering from overcapacity. In <a href="https://www.fmprc.gov.cn/mfa_eng/xwfw_665399/s2510_665401/2511_665403/202404/t20240430_11291753.html">a speech on April 30</a> , Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman Lin Jian argued that China&#39;s exports simply represent the country taking its natural place as the world&#39;s manufacturer:</p><blockquote><p> The “China overcapacity” accusation may look like an economic discussion, but the truth is, the accusation is built on false logic and ignores more than 200 years of the basic concept of comparative advantage in Western economics. All countries produce and export products of their comparative advantage and this is the nature of international trade.</p></blockquote><p> Lin is slightly misapplying the theory of comparative advantage here. Comparative advantage explains <em>balanced</em> trade — I give you soybeans because I&#39;m good at growing soybeans, you give me cars in exchange for soybeans because you&#39;re good at making cars, and so on. It can&#39;t explain <em>unbalanced</em> trade — you give me cars in exchange for IOUs. Trade surpluses and deficits require ideas that go beyond comparative advantage.</p><p> But Lin&#39;s core belief here is that manufacturing is simply what China does best, and that fundamental economic factors dictate that China should do more of it, and other countries should do correspondingly less. Perhaps in the end, trade will balance out, and other countries will deindustrialize and become farms, financial service providers, and so on, while China makes all their goods.</p><p> This isn&#39;t <em>such</em> a far-fetched notion. In the 20th century, Europe, the US, and a few countries in East Asia made most of the world&#39;s manufactured goods, so it&#39;s possible for manufacturing to be very geographically concentrated. And China has an enormous fundamental strength that no other country has (except perhaps a future India) — its vast internal market.</p><p> China has a vast number of consumers, who will tend to prefer Chinese products (out of cultural proximity, even without taking nationalism into account). That huge domestic market allows Chinese manufacturers to reach enormous <em>scale</em> , driving their costs down relative to companies in other countries, even before they export anything. It also allows China to have a vast network of <em>suppliers</em> for every type of manufacturing, without having to order many parts and materials abroad. And it tends to create <em>clustering effects</em> , where all the EV makers or chipmakers want to go to China because that&#39;s where the greatest numbers of their competitors are located; companies like to poach employees and appropriate ideas from their competitors.</p><p> So it&#39;s possible that China&#39;s massive flood of exports is <a href="https://www.pekingnology.com/p/lan-xiaohuan-on-chinas-local-government">simply a transitory stage</a> in a long-term shift of global manufacturing to its natural location. Chinese economic planners <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/newsletters/2024-01-08/world-economy-latest-china-the-amazon-economy?sref=R8NfLgwS">may believe</a> that accelerating this inevitable shift is the best way to boost their country&#39;s growth:</p><blockquote><p> “China wants to be the Amazon of countries — Amazon is the everything store, China wants to be the &#39;make everything&#39; country,” said Damien Ma of US think tank Macropolo, who met senior policymakers in Beijing last year. “The vision is to bring a complete supply chain to China.”</p></blockquote><p> There are some issues with this theory, of course. Why would an inevitable transition need such massive subsidies? Why would comparative advantage manifest as many decades of unbalanced trade? But basically, I think something like this theory is what many Chinese policymakers either believe — or will profess to believe, in order to defend China from accusations of “overcapacity”.</p><h4> Theory 4: Forced deindustrialization</h4><p> There is another, darker version of the “comparative advantage” theory. This is the notion that China is intentionally trying to wreck the manufacturing industries of its geopolitical rivals, in order to gain a military advantage over them.</p><p> In any major protracted war, industrial capacity becomes extremely important. Civilian manufacturing gets repurposed for military use. The most famous example is when the US <a href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/book-review-freedoms-forge">out-manufactured its opponents</a> in World War 2. The US still has a law called the Defense Production Act that&#39;s supposed to allow a repeat of the civilian-to-military factory conversion.</p><p> The larger a percent of global manufacturing China has, and lower a percent its rivals have, the better its chances would be of overwhelming those rivals in a war. Gaining a commanding share of global manufacturing might even allow China to displace the US and its allies as the world&#39;s dominant power — something the country&#39;s leaders have <a href="https://www.brookings.edu/articles/the-long-game-chinas-grand-strategy-to-displace-american-order/">repeatedly said they want to do</a> — without a fight. Currently, the blocs are about evenly matched: </p><div class="captioned-image-container"><figure><a class="image-link is-viewable-img image2" target="_blank" href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg" data-component-name="Image2ToDOM"><div class="image2-inset"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_webp,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw"><img src="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg" width="1456" height="821" data-attrs="{&quot;src&quot;:&quot;https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg&quot;,&quot;srcNoWatermark&quot;:null,&quot;fullscreen&quot;:null,&quot;imageSize&quot;:null,&quot;height&quot;:821,&quot;width&quot;:1456,&quot;resizeWidth&quot;:null,&quot;bytes&quot;:171766,&quot;alt&quot;:null,&quot;title&quot;:null,&quot;type&quot;:&quot;image/jpeg&quot;,&quot;href&quot;:null,&quot;belowTheFold&quot;:true,&quot;topImage&quot;:false,&quot;internalRedirect&quot;:null}" class="sizing-normal" alt="" srcset="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_424,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 424w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_848,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 848w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1272,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 1272w, https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/w_1456,c_limit,f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F59e51dc6-b416-464b-ad56-e3ecfe17003e_1492x841.jpeg 1456w" sizes="100vw" loading="lazy"></picture><div class="image-link-expand"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" class="lucide lucide-maximize2 "><polyline points="15 3 21 3 21 9"></polyline><polyline points="9 21 3 21 3 15"></polyline><line x1="21" x2="14" y1="3" y2="10"></line><line x1="3" x2="10" y1="21" y2="14"></line></svg></div></div><figcaption class="image-caption"> Source: <a href="https://cepr.org/voxeu/columns/china-worlds-sole-manufacturing-superpower-line-sketch-rise">CEPR</a></figcaption></figure></div><p> The Second China Shock might tip that balance decisively in China&#39;s favor.</p><p> Comparative advantage, on its own, probably won&#39;t be enough to make that happen. Usually, when new countries added themselves to the roster of high-output, high-tech manufacturers, they didn&#39;t cause wholesale deindustrialization in other countries.第一次中国冲击恰逢美国<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/MANEMP">制造业就业</a>的大幅下降，但实际的制造业产量仍然<a href="https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/OUTMS">差不多</a>。</p><p> That&#39;s where subsidies could come in. If Chinese government subsidies make it essentially impossible for any non-Chinese company to compete, it could artificially tip the balance of comparative advantage, to the point where the US, Europe, Japan, and Korea could be inefficiently bereft of manufacturing industries — at least as long as China keeps up the subsidies. That window of time might be enough for China to accomplish its military objectives (eg conquering Taiwan), and establishing itself as the global hegemon.</p><p>这样的结果是美国和其他人自然希望预防的结果，我敢打赌，强迫去工业化的威胁在于精心制作新关税的人们的脑海中。</p><h4>理论5：XI Jinping的技术历史理论</h4><p>我们永远无法解雇的一种可能性是，中国仅仅是因为它有一个绝对的统治者决定做这些事情。战略翻译中心主任坦纳·格里尔（Tanner Greer）<a href="https://scholars-stage.org/saving-china-through-science-and-technology/">认为</a>，习近平及其手工挑选的下属痴迷于推动中国的伟大，通过垄断未来的一些高科技行业：</p><blockquote><p>在习近平总统的认可和中国政策精英中受欢迎的这一想法中，这一想法认为，人类历史有铰链。中国领导人认为，在这些罕见的时刻，新兴技术可以推翻现有的经济秩序……大英帝国和美国升入了全球霸权，因为每个帝国都率先进行了全球技术经济革命。现在过去重复了。人类再次发现自己是科学动荡的悬崖。全球经济增长的基础即将转变，XI确定中国将领导这种转型……</p><p> XI向[2016年]举行的中国科学家聚集了[所有这些]的逻辑……。xi<a href="https://news.12371.cn/2016/05/31/ARTI1464698194635743.shtml">认为</a>“历史经验表明[这些技术革命都深刻地改变了全球发展模式。”一些州“抓住”了这个“难得的机会”。其他人没有。那些认识到他们面前的革命并积极利用它的人“迅速提高了他们的经济实力，科学和技术力量以及国防能力，从而迅速增强了他们的综合民族实力。”</p></blockquote><p>这听起来像是一堆马克思主义的Mumbo-Jumbo，但实际上与其他国家对技术，工业和国家利益的看法并没有很大不同。例如，如果您阅读了<a href="https://www.whitehouse.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/02-2022-Critical-and-Emerging-Technologies-List-Update.pdf">白宫关于“批判性和新兴技术”的报告</a>，那么该语言的千禧年有点少，但是基本思想是可以识别的 - 如果您希望您的国家强大 - 高科技行业尽可能多。</p><p>至于这些关键技术是什么，中国政府和美国政府似乎都不太确定 - 相反，他们在许多行业中都会放置多元化的赌注，以防万一这些行业成为未来的关键。格里尔写道：</p><blockquote><p>当中国高级领导层谈论即将到来的技术科学革命时，他们提到了AI，但仅在一长串有前途的技术的背景下。其中包括材料科学，遗传学和植物育种，神经科学，量子计算，绿色能源和航空工程。在习近平的言论中，这些都不是其他人的特权。</p></blockquote><p>那是一个令人难以置信的一般清单。但是，也许习近平和政治局认为中国需要大量补贴<em>所有</em>这些事情，以最大程度地提高其成为明天世界中超级大国的机会。出口繁荣可能是该决定的下游。</p><h4>理论6：战争准备</h4><p>最后一个理论是最黑暗的理论，我只会听到霍克民族安全界喃喃自语。这是中国以补贴驱动的制造繁荣代表战争生产的开始的想法。</p><p>该理论基本上有两个部分。首先，正如我提到的，战争中的国家将平民生产线转变为军事生产。因此，建立容易转换为军事用途的钢铁和计算机筹码等民用行业可能是为这种转换做准备的一种方式。纳撒尼尔·谢尔（Nathaniel Sher）以国家利益的方式写作，假设了<a href="https://nationalinterest.org/feature/china%E2%80%99s-economic-slowdown-strengthening-its-defense-industrial-base-210506">这些方面的一些事情</a>：</p><blockquote><p>中国的放缓掩盖表面上是一个令人担忧的趋势：北京以加速的速度向高科技制造投资了……中国的新工业政策可以帮助它缩小与美国的能力差距……房地产部门的弱点正在释放资源 - 释放资源 - 释放资源 -   - 释放资源 - 释放资源 - 土地，劳动力，资本和中间投入 - 投资于双重使用部门。在航空，电子和通信设备等<a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-goes-all-in-on-green-industry-to-jolt-ailing-economy-2f836395">行业</a>中，增长尤其强劲。到明年，政府计划将“ <a href="https://english.news.cn/20240206/f49cd933c0d042a0ade9c673afa67f37/c.html#:~:text=The%20share%20of%20strategic%20emerging,over%2017%20percent%20by%202025.">战略新兴行业</a>”的产出从13％增加到17％…</p><p>从历史上看，美国的主要工业基础使其能够在大电力战争中发挥关键作用……如今，美国的消费者和服务主导的经济不适合维持一场重大战争。</p><p>相比之下，中国现在占<a href="https://www.wsj.com/world/china/china-goes-all-in-on-green-industry-to-jolt-ailing-economy-2f836395">全球制造业</a>的31％，即使其工业<a href="https://www.stats.gov.cn/english/PressRelease/202402/t20240201_1947121.html">能力利用率</a>低于潜力。对先进制造业的持续投资只会进一步提高中国的战略能力。</p></blockquote><p>其次，战争中的任何国家都容易削减供应线，因此建立筹码等关键组成部分的国内制造是使国家免受制裁和封锁的一种方式。在习近平的领导下，中国工业政策的重点是陆上整个供应链，目前的大型制造业推动仍在<a href="https://warontherocks.com/2024/04/china-is-battening-down-for-the-gathering-storm-over-taiwan/">继续这种趋势</a>：</p><blockquote><p>习近平<a href="https://www.merics.org/en/report/comprehensive-national-security-unleashed-how-xis-approach-shapes-chinas-policies-home-and">对经济</a>的绝对优先级排序可能是所有战争准备指标中最有说服力的。仅在过去的18个月中，习近平就做出了巨大的努力，以使中国经济免受潜在的外部脆弱性的侵害，以牺牲增长为代价的自力更生。这种战略转变不仅与贸易战，感知的供应链漏洞或降低风险动态有关。习近平似乎已经研究了西方对乌克兰的制裁手册，随后采取了长长的保护措施，以弥补中国经济的孵化以抵抗类似的压力。</p></blockquote><p>这是所有人中最不祥的理论。这表明出口繁荣可能是偶然的，这是中国创建世界上最伟大的军事生产机器的意外副作用。</p><h4>那么哪个理论是对的？</h4><p>重要的是要重申，这些理论都不是相互排斥的。战争生产，工业政策，强迫对竞争对手的去工业化以及衰退打击的目标可能只是在中国领导人的心中保持一致。而且，诸如中国衰退和制造业的长期转变之类的自然力量可能会为政府的努力提供帮助。<em>所有这些理论都可能立即正确。</em>也许只有其中的一些子集。</p><p>但是我认为以这种方式破坏可能性是仔细思考关税和其他贸易保护主义措施实际上希望实现的目标的有用前奏。 </p><div><hr></div><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Subscribe now&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"><a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/subscribe?"><span>现在订阅</span></a></p><p class="button-wrapper" data-attrs="{&quot;url&quot;:&quot;https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-china-producing-so-many-export?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share&quot;,&quot;text&quot;:&quot;Share&quot;,&quot;action&quot;:null,&quot;class&quot;:null}" data-component-name="ButtonCreateButton"> <a class="button primary" href="https://www.noahpinion.blog/p/why-is-china-producing-so-many-export?utm_source=substack&utm_medium=email&utm_content=share&action=share"><span>分享</span></a></p><p></p><div class="footnote" data-component-name="FootnoteToDOM"><a id="footnote-1" href="#footnote-anchor-1" class="footnote-number" contenteditable="false" target="_self">1</a><div class="footnote-content"><p>注意：这不是“倾销”的技术定义。从技术上讲，“倾销”是指一个国家以海外销售产品的价格低于国内市场的价格低。在中国的情况下，像电动汽车这样的出口通常比中国<em>更高的</em>海外价格。</p></div></div> ;
